<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-201-224  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 201 224.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC-Computing  May 1989 v2 n5 p274(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The laser printer: how it works.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Catchings, Bill; Van Name, Mark L.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   The working parts of a laser printer. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>The Laser PrinterandM;Every time you send a page to a laser printer, you're setting in motion acomplex series of steps as efficiently organized as a factory and asprecisely choreographed as a ballet.andP;  Gutenberg would have been impressed.andM;The parts that make up a laser printer represent the highest state ofprinting technology, including laser imaging, precise paper movement, andmicroprocessor control of all its actions.andM;To create the nearly typeset-quality output that is characteristic of a laserprinter, the machine must interpret the signals coming from a computer,translating those signals into instructions that control the movement of alaser beam and the paper handler.andP;  Paper is sensitized so that it will acceptthe black toner that makes up the image; then that image must be fused to thepaper.andP;  At the heart of the printer is the print engine, a device that owesits ancestry to photocopiers.andP;  An important part of this engine is a cylindernamed the organic photoconducting cartridge (OPC), which is sometimes simplycalled &quot;the drum.&quot;andM;The OPC is the part of the engine that transfers an image--whether made up ofletters, graphics, or a combination of both--to the paper.andP;  It is coated witha film (usually zinc oxide and other materials) that is charged with eithernegative or positive static electricity.andP;  If any portion of the drum's filmis exposed to light, the charge on the exposed surface is reversed.andM;Because the OPC rotates, it is involved in five operations occurring at thesame time.andO;</TEXT></DOC>